occurrences.line_text: As for vs two, least doubt of vs ye haue,
Fearing least from her cage the wearie soule would flit.
At least it faire endeuour will apply.
Trembling through feare, least down he fallen should,
Their safetie, least by searching daungers new,
And he that happie seemes and least in payne,
Fearing least she your loues away should woo,
Fearing least if she should him freely set,
To which they all repayr'd, both most and least,
And she, that with her least word can asswage
Least did she thinke, that which he most concealed,
And from the most, that some were giuen to the least?
vThat doest not know the least thing of them all?
Yet the least word that euer could be layd
He fear'd least they with shame would him pursew.
And gan to doubt, least she him sought t'appeach
Yet doubting least his hold was but vnsound,
Whose life did lie in her least eye-lids fall;
Sometime she feared, least some hard mishap
Sometime least his false foe did him entrap
Least some new loue had him from her possest;
In minde he grew, for feare least by that art
Not suffering the least twinckling sleepe to start
But if the least appear'd, her eyes she streight reprieued.
Least any should betray his Lady treacherously.
Least any more such practise should proceede.
Least by such slight he were vnwares deceiued;
To saue her selfe, least that he did her slay:
Least ye therefore mote happily me blame,
Therefore misdoubting, least he should misguyde
Least that the beasts sharpe teeth had any wound
Gainst all, both good and bad, both most and least,
Least if men you of cruelty accuse,
And least he should recouer foote againe,
Least vnto me betide a greater ill;
Fearing least he at length the raines would lend
Least they should ioyne against the weaker side,
Was almost dead, misdoubting least of new
Euen vnto the lowest and the least.
Which she streight way for dread least, if her syre
That much he feared, least reprochfull blame
And ransacke all their dennes from most to least,
Them list no lenger there at leasure dwell,
My leasure, so long leaues here to repeat:
And scarse them leasure gaue, her passing to behold.
Who finding litle leasure her to wooe,
But leasure had, and libertie to frame
But the fresh Swayne would not his leasure dwell,
Then gan the Prince at leasure to inquire
And vnto Ladies loue would lend no leasure:
But drew him on with hope, fit leasure to awayt.
That they mote treat of things abrode at leasure;
And after all an army strong she leau'd,
Your owne deare sake forst me at first to leaue
O leaue her soone, or let her soone be slaine.
The Lyon would not leaue her desolate,
As you to leaue, that haue me loued still,
The earth shall sooner leaue her kindly skill
Then I leaue you, my liefe, yborne of heauenly berth.
Her seruile beast yet would not leaue her so,
To leaue them to; but thorough daily care
Leaue off their worke, vnmindfull of their smart,
The faire Duess' had forst him leaue behind;
Leaue roaring, when in rage he for reuenge did earne.
For loue of me leaue off this dreadfull play;
Nor leaue his stand, vntill his Captaine bed.
Arise, Sir knight arise, and leaue this cursed place.
Disdeining life, desiring leaue to die,
And Ladies loue to leaue so dearely bought?
So leaue they take of Coelia, and her daughters three.
But thought his armes to leaue, and helmet to vnlace.
To see faire heauens face, and life not leaue,
Loe I for pledges leaue. So giue me leaue to rest.
Loe I for pledges leaue. So giue me leaue to rest.
Leaue, ah leaue off, what euer wight thou bee,
Leaue, ah leaue off, what euer wight thou bee,
Depart to woods vntoucht, & leaue so proud disdaine?
And soone leaue off this toylesome wearie stoure;
Guyon was loath to leaue his guide behind,
Ne gaue him leaue to bid that aged sire
And leaue the rudenesse of that antique age
If thee list not, leaue haue thou to refuse:
But giue me leaue to follow mine emprise.
How oft do they, their siluer bowers leaue,
But leaue these relicks of his liuing might,
If not, leaue vnto me thy knights last patronage.
Dyes not, when breath the bodie first doth leaue,
Crau'd leaue of Alma, and that aged sire,
A little leaue vnto a rusticke Muse
For knight to leaue his Ladie were great shame,
Where thee yet shall he leaue for memory
To leaue that desert mansion, she cast
Him forst to leaue his pray, for to attend
To leaue to him that Lady for excheat,
It yrkes me, leaue thee in this wofull state,
Both were full loth to leaue that needfull tent,
To take to his new loue, and leaue her old despysd.
And loth to leaue his liefest pelfe behind,
Then is it best (said he) that ye doe leaue
Tho gan he her perswade, to leaue that lewd
And leaue me to my former languishing;
And gaue her leaue at pleasure forth to passe.
That being forst his saddle soone to leaue,
Which done, she passed forth not taking leaue,
Yet leaue vnto his sorrow did not yeeld,
That forced him to leaue his loftie sell,
And bad them leaue their labours and long toyle,
I vow, you dead or liuing not to leaue,
And loth to leaue her late betrothed make,
And yeelded leaue, how euer malcontent
Full oftentimes she leaue of him did take;
He would her shortly leaue, and former loue forget.
And taking leaue of all, with him did beare
And folly seem'd to leaue the thing vndonne,
And leaue his loue in that sea-walled fort.
Which to another place I leaue to be perfected.
Not so to leaue her, nor away to cast,
As that ye would for little leaue the same,
Therefore leaue off to weigh them all againe,
None was debard, but all had leaue that lust.
There leaue we them in pleasure and repast,
Leaue nought vnpromist, that may him perswade,
Yet taking leaue of her, he did depart.
Then taking leaue of them, she forward went,
We did him leaue, after that he had foyled
They both resoluing now to leaue the place,
To leaue his proper forme, and other shape to take.
Then taking humble leaue of that great Queene,
Gaue leaue vnto his ghost from thraldome bound,
There did the Prince him leaue in deadly swound,
Of whom yet taking leaue, thenceforth he went
For from the day that he thus did it leaue,
To leaue the loue, that ye before embraced,
And lends vnto it leaue the emptie ayre to beat.
He tooke his leaue of her, there left in heauinesse.
Then since the saluage Island I did leaue
So both tooke goodly leaue, and parted seuerall.
Leaue faytor quickely that misgotten weft
I leaue to you, for aye me to disgrace
My loues owne part to leaue so suddenly,
To leaue his loue he should be ill apayd,
So taking courteous leaue, they parted twayne,
There to their fortune leaue we them awhile,
He her not finding, both them thus nigh dead did leaue.
To leaue, till to her fathers house he had her brought.
Yet if he needes will fight, craue leaue till morne,
He could him force to loose, or leaue his enterprize.
She saw now left, she cast to leaue the place,
Was forced there to leaue them both behynd,
Of that good Hermite both they tooke their leaue,
And went both on their way, ne ech would other leaue.
Would not her leaue alone in her great need.
But if ye please to lend me leaue a while,
Ne list me leaue my loued libertie,
Vnto your selfe I freely leaue to chose,
Whether I shall you leaue, or from these villaines lose.
So humbly taking leaue, she turnd aside,
As her to leaue in such a piteous plight.
To them, that list, the worlds gay showes I leaue,
Giue leaue awhyle, good father, in this shore
That he should neuer leaue, nor be delayd
So taking leaue of that same gentle swaine,
Ne stayeth leaue to take, before his friends doe dye.
So leaue we her in wretched thraldome bound,
To leaue his Loue, now perill being past,
So taking leaue of his faire Pastorell,
There leaue we them in ioy, and let vs tell
Huge heapes of mudd he leaues, wherein there breed
And their greene leaues trembling with euery blast,
He leaues the welkin way most beaten plaine,
In greene vine leaues he was right fitly clad;
Which through the tre[m]bling leaues full gently playes
When morning deaw vpon their leaues doth light:
My narrow leaues cannot in them containe
And flourishing fresh leaues and blossomes did enwrap.
To laugh at shaking of the leaues light,
Clothed with leaues, that none the wood mote see
My leasure, so long leaues here to repeat:
As withered leaues drop from their dried stockes,
And the tall trees with leaues apparelled,
Their tender buds or leaues to violate,
Which did themselues emongst the leaues enfold,
His locks, like faded leaues fallen to grownd,
But lapped vp her silken leaues most chaire,
Beates downe both leaues and buds without regard,
Emongst the shadie leaues, their sweet abode,
The rest he leaues in ground: so takes in hond
Those cursed leaues, his charmes backe to reuerse;
With oaken leaues attrapt, that seemed fit
Dispreds the glorie of her leaues gay;
Like as a flowre, whose silken leaues small,
with th'Hermit leaues behynd.
Which may her feeble leaues with comfort glade.
Out quenched, leaues no skill nor difference of wight.
That like a rose her silken leaues did faire vnfold.
The false Duessa leauing noyous Night,
For ransome leauing him the late borne childe;
Vpbrayd, for leauing her in place vnmeet,
But leauing all behind her, fled away:
Leauing behind them griefe and heauinesse.
And leauing heauens kingdome, here did roue
But leauing watry gods, as booting nought,
But leauing him forth on his iourney far'd:
Whom leauing there in that dispiteous plight,
And leauing Artegall to his owne care;
And leauing there this Ladie all dismayd,
The villaine leauing him vnto his mate
And leauing home, to roiall court I sought;
Not sparing wight, ne leauing any balke,
Chirpe loud to thee out of their leauy cages,
Such one was Lecherie, the third of all this traine.
And next to him rode lustfull Lechery,
And foorth they passe, with pleasure forward led,
Led with delight, they thus beguile the way,
His wanton dayes that euer loosely led,
Will was his guide, and griefe led him astray.
To meete me wandring, who perforce me led
And towards it a broad high way that led,
May seeme the wayne was very euill led,
His life he led in lawlesse riotise;
He led a wretched life vnto him selfe vnknowne.
Vpon a Lion, loth for to be led;
Led her away into a forrest wilde,
He led away with courage stout and bold.
Led with their noise, which through the aire was thrown:
Led with thy prayses and broad-blazed fame,
Then called she a Groome, that forth him led
And alwayes led, to her with reuerence rare
Which to a goodly Citie led his vew;
The fond encheason, that me hither led.
Which to auenge, he to this place me led,
She led him vp into a goodly bowre,
led into loose desire,
Into a shadie dale she soft him led,
By fortune came, led with the troublous sowne:
Is by him tempted, & led downe,
Through that thicke couert he him led, and found
Thence forward he him led, and shortly brought
And thence him forward led, him further to entise.
Yet forcing it to faine, him forth thence led
First she them led vp to the Castle wall,
Who passing by, forth led her guestes anone
Thence backe againe faire Alma led them right,
But Alma thence the[m] led to th'hindmost roome of three.
A priuate life led in Albania,
Was by Maximian lately led away,
And led him to the Castle by the beaten way.
Then led they her away, and eke that knight
They with them led, both sorrowfull and sad:
These straunger knights through passing, forth were led
She caused them be led in curteous wize
The same one day, as me misfortune led,
Led with eternall prouidence, that has
In th'euening late old Glauce thither led
Into that forest farre they thence him led,
Thus as he led the Beast along the way,
And without reskew led her quite away.
Where he through fatall errour long was led
And with him led to sea an youthly trayne,
Her vp they tooke, and with them home her led,
Came dauncing forth, and with them nimbly led
Led of two grysie villeins, th'one Despight,
And captiue with her led to wretchednesse and wo.
By which fraile youth is oft to follie led,
That still are led with euery light report.
For Loue is free, and led with selfe delight,
Led with that wofull Ladies piteous crying,
She drew her far, and led with slow delay.
Of many Nations into thraldome led,
In presence of them all forth led her thence:
But forth I led her through the Temple gate,
Nor no entreatie to his loue be led;
The foolish Kyte, led with licentious will,
She causd to be attacht, and forthwith led
Was thence by them into the Temple led;
That Damzell, led her to the Souldans right.
Thenceforth into that Castle he her led,
So him they led through all their streetes along,
Wandred about the fields, as liking led
Therein the Hermite, which his life here led
He thence them led into his Hermitage,
Led by a Carle and foole, which by her side did passe.
This was Disdaine, who led that Ladies horse
Led in a rope, which both his hands did bynd;
He like a dog was led in captiue case,
The whiles his Pastorell is led,
Long time, as fit occasion forth them led;
And all his people captiue led away;
Led with the infants cry, that loud did weepe,
So led this Knight his captyue with like conquest wonne.
To win faire Leda to his louely trade:
With whom he ledd a long and happie life;
And could the ledden of the Gods vnfold,
The wanton Lee, that oft doth loose his way,
The spreading Lee, that like an Island fayre
His corps was carried downe along the Lee,
In hast vnto his Lord, where he him left afore.
He so vngently left her, whom she loued best.
She soone left off her mirth and wanton play,
His Lady left as a prise martiall,
So left her, where she now is turnd to treen mould.
Drunke vp his life; his corse left on the strand.
And sooth to say, why I left you so long,
He left him lying so, ne would no lenger stay.
Left in the hand of that same Paynim bold,
Who now is left to keepe the forlorne maid
Whom when she found, as she him left in plight,
That of Hippolytus was left no moniment.
As her outrageous foe had left her late,
The gentle virgin left behind alone
Foreby a fountaine, where I late him left
And left the doubtfull battell hastily,
He left his stond, and her pursewd apace,
Where she had left, the noble Redcrosse knight,
And left to losse: his stalking steps are stayde
My last left comfort is, my woes to weepe and waile.
And well could rule: now he hath left you heare,
Where haue you left your Lord, that could so well you tosse?
He smote off his left arme, which like a blocke
He lightly left the foe, with whom he fought,
In one alone left hand he now vnites,
Was nothing left, but like an emptie bladder was.
That soone in him was left no one corrupted iot.
Was woxen strong, and left her fruitfull nest;
Which as a stocke he left vnto his seede;
And her base Elfin brood there for thee left.
Close vnder his left wing, then broad displayd.
And left not any marke, where it did light;
Where he hath left his plumes all hoary gray,
Fiue ioynts thereof he hewd, and but the stump him left.
The which he shortly did, and Vna left to mourne.
Whom Princes late displeasure left in bands,
His shackles emptie left, him selfe escaped cleene.
Whom late I left in langourous constraint?
So they him left, inflam'd with wrathfulnesse,
But wretched we, where ye haue left your marke,
Me then he left enwombed of this child,
Left thee for portion of thy liuelihed,
He left his loftie steed with golden sell,
Sith last I left that honorable place,
He left his steed without, and speare besyde,
And that weake eld hath left thee nothing wise,
And saw it stirre: she left her percing launce,
Therewith Sir Guyon left his first emprise,
And beckned him, the last helpe she had left:
But he that last left helpe away did take,
Where left, he went, and his owne false part playd,
But backe rebounding, left the forckhead keene;
That all his left side it did quite disarme;
So she him left, and did her selfe betake
Soone she that Island farre behind her left,
Where sleeping late she left her other knight.
There by his maister left, when late he far'd
Late left beyond that Ydle lake, proceedes
And their vile carcases now left vnburied.
The Palmer seeing his left empty place,
Yet since no way is left to wreake my spight,
And left his headlesse body bleeding all the place.
And many Giants left on groning flore;
He left three sonnes, his famous progeny,
And Locrine left chiefe Lord of Britany.
Locrine was left the soueraine Lord of all;
That in the end was left no moniment
And left two sonnes, of pearelesse prowesse both;
Fiue sonnes he left begotten of one wife,
Left of his life most famous memory,
He left two sonnes, too young to rule aright,
And left inglorious on the vanquisht playne,
Who dying left none heire them to withstand,
Three sonnes he dying left, all vnder age;
He left three sonnes, the which in order raynd,
He left two sonnes, of which faire Elferon
He dying left the fairest Tanaquill,
What now is left of miserable wights,
Which when she saw, she left her lockes vndight,
In her left hand a Cup of gold she held,
Nought but her louely face she for his looking left.
The wicked steele through his left side did glaunce;
Ne of thy late life memory is left,
But who that liues, is left to waile his losse:
She left, pursewing that same foster strong;
Who lately left the same, and tooke this way:
The want of his good Squire late left behind,
In his left thigh, and deepely did it thrill:
It left, but both did quite drye vp, and blast;
And left her blisfull bowre of ioy aboue,
Him for to seeke, she left her heauenly hous,
And so had left them languishing twixt hope and feare.
Where you him lately left, in Mars his bed;
He left his captiue Beast at liberty,
Where late he left the Beast, he ouercame,
Which Florimell had left behind her late,
But left his loue to losse, and fled himselfe apace.
To tell of Satyrane, where I him left of late.
From her left arme, to rest in glorious victorye.
The which he dying left next in remaine
My natiue soile haue left, my dayes to spend
And of his owne him left not liberty:
And left the fire; loue money ouercame:
He left his wife; money did loue disclame:
The gentle Lady, loose at randon left,
Whom he hath left in yonder forrest wyld:
That seem'd no helpe for him was left in liuing sight.
And nothing left, but like an aery Spright,
Whose hideous tayle his left foot did enfold,
Where late she left the pensife Scudamore,
She left Sir Scudamour in great distresse,
And left him now as sad, as whilome iollie,
More for the loue which he had left behynd,
As ye haue done for me: the left hand rubs the right.
And left the head behind: with which despight
And in his hand nought but the troncheon left,
But finding no fit seat, the lifelesse corse it left.
It left; but that same soule, which therein dwelt,
For either they were left vppon the land,
And left behind her in her secret bowre,
Who hauing left that restlesse house of Care,
The sacred pledge, which in his faith was left,
That where ye left, I may her seeke, as doth behoue.
Her freed, in which ye her all hopelesse left,
I found her not, where I her left whyleare,
She left him to his fortunes gouernment,
To Scudamour, who she had left behind:
Had left that Turneyment for beauties prise,
And therein left the pike head of his speare.
Hauing his carrion corse quite sencelesse left,
She left the gentle Squire with Amoret:
He left him there in languor to remaine,
Yet hath he left one daughter that is hight
Had left in his protection whileare,
Left in the victors powre, like vassall bond;
(As they supposd) but her had to her liking left.
And left them groning there vpon the plaine.
Left a fayre Ladie languishing in payne:
The dongeon was, in which her bound he left,
So left he her withouten remedie.
But when she parted hence, she left her groome
And left me here, both his & mine owne loue to morne.
So were they left Lords of the field alone:
The which of all her spoyle was onely left;
Who hauing lately left that louely payre,
And former liuelod fayle, she left me quight,
Who taking her from me, his owne loue left astray.
As thing at randon left, to whom he list.
They left behind them, glad to be so quit:
By chaunce beheld, he left the bloudy slaughter,
Left to her will by his owne wilfull blame,
What now is left Clarinda? what remaines,
And to their sire their carcasses left to bestow.
Fled fast into the towne, and her sole victor left.
That he no worke at all left for the leach:
For else he sure had left not one aliue,
But left his loue, albe her strong request,
And left there dead. Meane while the other Knight
And left their scorched path yet in the firmament.
And his faire limbs left in the woods forlorne;
There they him left a carrion outcast;
Had left her now but fiue of all that brood:
The woefull widow had no meanes now left,
What is there else (sayd he) left of their rout?
In filthy durt, and left so in the loathely soyle.
Who hauing left Mercilla, streight way went
Whiles she alone is left, and thou here found?
They spide a Lady left all succourlesse,
Meant them to haue incountred, ere they left the shore.
That on the ground he left full many a corse;
Not one was left, that durst her once haue disobayd.
He tooke his leaue of her, there left in heauinesse.
Eftsoones he loosd that Squire, and so him left,
And in his left he held a sharpe borespeare,
And left sore wounded: but when her he mist,
Vnto the place, where me he left behind:
For which the onely helpe now left them last
Witnesse thereof he shew'd his head there left,
There left on ground, though in full euill plight,
And his sad Ladie left in pitifull affright.
Had left that couple, nere their vtmost cast.
Which earst he left, he signes vnto them made,
But Calepine, now being left alone
She saw now left, she cast to leaue the place,
Had left behind, he gan eftsoones prepare,
Now left alone in great extremity,
That few of them he left aliue, which fled,
As one that had no life him left through former feare.
He had behynd him left that saluage wight,
He had not left one limbe of him vnrent:
Where seeing him so lie, he left his steed,
And his left hand vpon his collar layd.
Whom late we left ryding vpon an Asse,
Loue hath the glory of his kingdome left,
He left his lofty steede to aide him neare,
Backe to the furrow which I lately left;
I lately left a furrow, one or twayne
And toyle endured, sith I left him last
In th'open fields an Infant left alone,
Now seeing Calidore left all alone,
Had left, now gan afresh to rancle sore,
Her selfe sole left, a second spoyle to bee
What now is left her, but to wayle and weepe,
They left her so, in charge of one the best
